 # BlockBustre RBAC Permissions

This document outlines the 16 permissions used in the BlockBustre Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) system.

## Overview

The RBAC system uses Django's standard CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) permission pattern with `add_`, `view_`, `change_`, and `delete_` prefixes for each model.

## 16 Permissions by Category

### User Management (4 permissions)

- **`add_user`** - Create new users
- **`change_user`** - Edit existing users
- **`delete_user`** - Delete users
- **`view_user`** - View user information

### Role Management (4 permissions)

- **`add_role`** - Create new roles
- **`change_role`** - Edit existing roles
- **`delete_role`** - Delete roles
- **`view_role`** - View role information

### Smart Contract Management (4 permissions)

- **`add_smartcontract`** - Create new smart contracts
- **`change_smartcontract`** - Edit existing smart contracts
- **`delete_smartcontract`** - Delete smart contracts
- **`view_smartcontract`** - View smart contract information

### Transaction Management (4 permissions)

- **`add_transaction`** - Create new transactions
- **`change_transaction`** - Edit existing transactions
- **`delete_transaction`** - Delete transactions
- **`view_transaction`** - View transaction information

## Permission Distribution by Role

### Admin Role
- **Permissions**: All 16 permissions (full access)
- **Description**: Complete system access with all CRUD operations

### Manager Role
- **Permissions**: 6 permissions
  - `view_user`, `change_user`
  - `view_smartcontract`, `change_smartcontract`
  - `view_transaction`, `change_transaction`
- **Description**: Management access with limited admin capabilities

### User Role
- **Permissions**: 4 permissions
  - `view_smartcontract`, `add_smartcontract`
  - `view_transaction`, `add_transaction`
- **Description**: Standard user access for creating and viewing content

### Guest Role
- **Permissions**: 1 permission
  - `view_smartcontract`
- **Description**: Limited guest access for viewing contracts only

## Implementation Notes

- Permissions are automatically created by Django when models are migrated
- Roles can be managed through the Django admin interface
- Permission checks can be performed in views using decorators or mixins
- Frontend can check user permissions via API calls to determine UI visibility